[West Nile virus surveillance reports are up-dated to 6 Oct 2000. The
number of human cases has risen to 17 with one death. As predicted West
Nile virus appears to be moving further south, but the report of spread
northward over the St. Lawrence into Canada is still unconfirmed. Mod.CP

Connecticut
-----------
Date: 5 Oct 2000
Source: State of Connecticut Mosquito Management Program [edited
<http://dep.state.ct.us/mosquito/index.asp>

The State confirmed a fourth West Nile virus (WNV) positive horse in
Connecticut. The Middlefield horse had not traveled. Its condition is
improving. Other horses in the stable were reported to have no signs of
sickness.
Also, 7 additional WNV positive birds were found in 5 new towns. The birds
were collected 6-18 Sep 2000, from the towns of: Clinton (2 crows), East
Haven (1 crow), Guilford (1 crow), Lyme (1 crow), Redding (2 crows). As of
5 Oct 2000, 568 birds have tested positive for WNV ­ 561 crows and 2
bluejays, 2 robins, one dove, one finch, and one cowbird ­ from 72
different towns.
******
Maryland
--------
Date: 5 Oct 2000
Source: Montgomery County, West Nile Virus Information [edited
<http://www.co.mo.md.us/services/dep/Mosquito/home.htm>

The Department of Health and Mental Hygiene notified the Montgomery County
Public Health Services that 2 dead crows found in the Rockville area had
tested positive For West Nile virus. There have been no human cases
detected in Maryland. There is no immediate public health threat.
******
New Jersey State
----------------
Test Results as of 4 Oct 2000 [edited
<http://www.state.nj.us/health/cd/westnile/104results.htm>

Human Testing
In total, blood and/or spinal fluid samples from 42 residents have been or
are in the process of being tested for the presence of West Nile virus
(WNV). To date, 4 tests were positive, 17 were negative and 21 are pending.
These individuals either had symptoms or signs that met the established WNV
testing criteria or exhibited most of the symptoms and are from counties
where dead crows and/or mosquitoes with the virus have been discovered. New
Jersey's positive human cases include an 82-year old Little Falls man who
became ill 3 Sep 2000, was admitted to a hospital 3 days later, and died 14
Sep 2000. New Jersey's other human cases include a 43-year old Jersey City
man, a 54-year old man with dual residency in Brooklyn, N.Y., and Cliffside
Park, Bergen County, and a 72-year old Bayonne woman. All 3 individuals
have either recovered or are recovering.
Crow, Hawk & Falcon Testing
To date, 1 015 birds (1 014 crows and a cockatiel) found in 17 counties
have tested positive for the presence of WNV. Positive birds have been
found in Atlantic (1), Bergen (188), Burlington (11), Camden (3), Cape May
(3), Essex (99), Gloucester (4), Hudson (63), Hunterdon (5), Mercer (9),
Middlesex (213), Monmouth (146), Morris (49), Ocean (13), Passaic (79),
Somerset (24) and Union (105) Counties. The tests were conducted at the
Department of Health and Senior Services' lab in Trenton. A total of 1 772
crows have been accepted for testing this year.
Mosquito and House Sparrow and Testing
Thirty-seven mosquito pools collected in Bergen (20), Essex (1), Middlesex
(3), Monmouth (3), Passaic (8) and Sussex (2) Counties have tested positive
for the presence of WNV. In total, 14 020 mosquito pools from all 21
counties have been collected by the Rutgers Mosquito Research and Control
Unit and tested by the Department of Health and Senior Services and/or the CDC.
In addition to mosquitoes, the CDC also analyzed blood samples taken from
541 house sparrows collected in Bergen, Passaic and Sussex County in late
July. No sparrows with WNV were discovered in New Jersey.
Sentinel Chicken Testing
Blood samples are taken weekly from sentinel chicken flocks placed in all
21 counties and tested by the New Jersey Department of Agriculture for the
presence of WNV. To date, one chicken, stationed in Middlesex County, has
tested positive for WNV. The National Veterinary Services Lab (NVSL) in
Ames, Iowa, has confirmed the test results. Sentinel chickens previously
reported by the Monmouth County Mosquito Extermination Commission (8 Sep
2000) as being positive for WNV have been re-tested by the New Jersey
Department of Agriculture and NSVL and do not have the virus. The WNV
positive chicken reported today from Middlesex County is the first chicken
from the sentinel program to be found with the virus this year in New Jersey.
Horse Testing
A total of 11 horses from Atlantic (2), Burlington (2), Cape May (1),
Monmouth (2), Ocean (2) and Sussex (2) Counties have tested positive for
WNV. Equine testing is conducted by the New Jersey Department of
Agriculture's animal health laboratory in Trenton and results are sent to
NVSL for confirmation.

******
New York City
--------------
Date: 4 Oct 2000
Source: Dept. of Health, Press Release [edited
<http://www.ci.nyc.ny.us/html/doh/html/public/press00/pr110104.html>

The following is a summary of the West Nile virus findings in the New York
City area up to the present: 14 humans, 145 birds and 146 mosquito pools.
The break-down by Boroughs is as follows:
Staten Island, 55 birds, 111 mosquito pools,10 humans; Manhattan, 29 birds,
16 mosquito pools; Queens, 24 birds, 5 mosquito pools, 1 human; Bronx, 10
birds, 6 mosquito pools; Brooklyn, 27 birds, 8 mosquito pools, 2 humans
(both hospitalized), and 1 human with dual residency in Brooklyn and New
Jersey.
******
New York State
---------------
Date: 6 Oct 2000
Source: West Nile virus Updates [edited
<http://www.health.state.ny.us/nysdoh/westnile/index.htm>

Today, the New York State Health Department's Wadsworth Center laboratories
reported 27 West Nile virus positive birds: Albany, 1; Broome, 1; Delaware,
1; Erie, 1; New York City, 5 (Brooklyn, 4; Queens, 1); Madison, 1; Nassau,
2; Niagara, 1; Orange, 1; Putnam, 2; Rockland, 4; Suffolk, 1; Tioga, 1;
Ulster, 3; Wayne, 1; and Westchester, 1. The West Nile virus positive bird
from Wayne County is the first positive West Nile virus specimen from that
county.
One West Nile virus positive mosquito pool was found in Columbia County.
The West Nile virus positive mosquito pool from Columbia County is the
first West Nile virus positive pool from that county.
National Veterinary Services Laboratories (NVSL) reported 1 West Nile virus
positive horse from Orange County.
The total number of West Nile virus positive specimens from New York State
for this year is 1 038 birds, 317 mosquito pools, 2 sentinel chickens, 7
live wild birds, 14 bats, 7 horses, 2 cats, 2 raccoons, 3 domestic rabbits,
3 squirrels, 1 chipmunk and 14 human cases.
******
US Department of Agriculture
----------------------------
Date: 30 Sep 2000
Source: Update for the period 24 through 30 Sep 2000 [edited
<http://www.aphis.usda.gov/oa/wnv/wnvstats.html>

A total of 6 horses were classified as having cases of West Nile virus
(WNV) infection this week. The National Veterinary Services Laboratories
(NVSL) found that all 6 were WNV-positive on a 1:1000 dilution (or greater)
of serum on IgM-capture enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay (ELISA). Five of
the horses also had WNV-positive results on a 1:10 dilution (greater) of
serum on a plaque reduction neutralization test (PRNT) and, based on their
history of clinical illness, were classified as confirmed cases. The sixth
horse, from Middletown, New York, was classified as a probable case. This
brings to 15 the total number of equine cases of WNV infection in 2000.
Equine cases of WNV infection in the United States, 2000:
1 - Staten Island, New York - 26 y.o. gelding; onset 8/17, euthanatized 8/20
2 - Wakefield, Rhode Island - 2 y.o. mare; onset 8/23, euthanatized 8/28
3 - Tuckahoe, New Jersey - 6 y.o. gelding; onset 8/27, euthanatized 8/30
4 - Bedford, Massachusetts - 12 y.o. gelding; onset 8/26, euthanatized 8/29
5 - Egg Harbor, New Jersey - 10 y.o. gelding; onset 8/29 or before, still
alive
6 - Danbury, Connecticut - 18 y.o.; onset 9/07, euthanatized 9/07
7 - Milford, Connecticut - 13 y.o. mare; onset 9/06, still alive
8 - Hebron, Connecticut - 21 y.o. gelding; onset 9/05, euthanatized (date
unknown)
9 - Lafayette, New Jersey - 20 y.o. gelding; onset 9/06 or before, still alive
10 - Andover, New Jersey - 7 y.o. stallion; onset 9/01, died 9/04
11 - Staten Island, New York - 38 y.o. mare; date of onset unknown, died
(date unknown)
12 - Middletown, New York - 16 y.o. mare; onset 9/04?, euthanatized 9/07
13 - Middletown, New York - 16 y.o. mare; onset 9/04?, still alive
14 - Middletown, New York - 17 y.o. gelding; onset 9/04?, still alive
15 - Hammonton, New Jersey - 14 y.o. mare; date of onset unknown, recovered
(but later euthanatized due to another problem)
The European Union previously issued import restrictions, in effect since
15 Sep 2000, for horses originating from the 5 States that have had an
equine case of WNV. No other countries have notified the USDA of any
WNV-related restrictions on the importation of horses.
6 additional mammals were reported as WNV-positive in New York this week,
including a raccoon and 2 cats from Albany County. Three squirrels were
also found positive in 3 different counties: Bronx, Kings, and Richmond.
There were 307 more birds reported as positive for WNV during the week. The
first confirmation of WNV activity in Pennsylvania was reported, as a total
of 4 positive crows were reported from 3 counties: Bucks, Chester, and
Delaware. Over 2 500 birds have now been documented as infected with WNV in
2000.
One new sentinel chicken was confirmed as WNV-positive in Queens County,
New York. The bird was located in Jamaica, New York, and was bled on 14
September. This is only the second sentinel bird found positive in 2000.
The cumulative totals for the period 1 May 2000 through 30 Sep 2000 are the
following: 16 humans, 15 equines, 25 other mammals, 2 510 birds, 350
mosquito pools, and 2 sentinel birds.
