[2
Date: 6 Oct 2000 11:30:54 GMT
From: M. Cosgriff <mcosgriff@hotmail.com>
Source: Washington Post, filed Fri 6 Oct 2000 [edited
<http://washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A19878-2000Oct5.html>

West Nile Virus Infected Crows In Washington D.C.
-------------------------------------------------
West Nile virus, the mosquito-borne illness that has moved inexorably
southward this year with the fall bird migration, has for the first time
appeared in the District and Montgomery County, officials said yesterday. A
total of 2 dead crows found in recent days in and around Rockville have
tested positive for the virus, along with 2 others from neighborhoods in
the District, according to Maryland and city officials. These discoveries
marked a geographic jump from the area south of Baltimore, where the virus
first turned up in Maryland 2 weeks ago, as well as the southernmost
extension of the virus since it appeared in the United States last year.
The state Department of Health and Mental Hygiene's announcement yesterday
also said that 6 more infected crows were found in Baltimore and Baltimore
County, bringing to 21 the number of infections found in the state.
Virginia officials said yesterday that no infected birds or mosquitoes had
been found there, although Suzanne Jenkins, assistant state epidemiologist,
said, "I wouldn't be surprised if it was here now and we just haven't found
it." No human infections have been reported in Maryland, Virginia or the
District.
[Byline: Michael E. Ruane and Avram Goldstein
