[3
Date: 6 Oct 2000 10:43:38 -0400
From: Edward Schroder <ESchroder@niaid.nih.gov>
Source: Baltimore Sun, Oct 6 2000 [edited

More West Nile Virus Infected Crows found in Baltimore
-------------------------------------------------------
The state's mosquito-spraying campaign moved into eastern Baltimore County
Thursday night after 2 dead crows infected with the West Nile virus were
found in Eastpoint and Dundalk. A total of 4 more infected crows were also
found in Baltimore, and 2 in Montgomery County - the first in the
Washington suburbs. In all, 21 infected crows have been found this year in
Maryland.
Also Thursday, Washington, D.C., announced the discovery of 2 infected
crows in that city's northwest section. The southward movement of the virus
in September and October is consistent with a federal government prediction
last week that the virus would spread south with fall bird migrations.
The pesticide Permethrin is being used in Maryland in the hope it will kill
enough adult mosquitoes to delay the inevitable entrenchment of the virus
in the local mosquito and bird populations. "There's no question it's in
the country to stay," said state Agriculture Department spokesman Don
Vandrey. In time, he said, West Nile-related spray campaigns will become "a
normal part of summer living." Baltimore Health Commissioner Peter L.
Beilenson said Thursday the spray campaign in the city is probably over for
the year because of cool weather, even though more dead crows are waiting
to be tested and may prove to be infected.
[Byline: Frank D. Roylance
