[4
Date: 5 Oct 2000 10:42:10 GMT-3
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Commonwealth of Pennsylvania Dept. of Health News Release, Wed, 4
Oct 2000 17:15:22 -0400 [edited

West Nile Virus Confirmed In Dauphin County Horse
-------------------------------------------------
HARRISBURG: On 4 Oct 2000, the Department of Health announced that West
Nile virus has been found in a horse in East Hanover Township, Dauphin
County. The 25-year-old infected horse from the Capital Area Therapeutic
Riding Association horse farm was put down on 22 Sep 2000 after it began to
show signs of encephalitis. The state Department of Agriculture and the
U.S. Department of Agriculture now have confirmed the horse's West Nile
virus infection.
This is the first confirmed case of West Nile infection in a Pennsylvanian
horse. An infected horse does not transmit the virus to people and does not
pose a threat to other horses or people who may have come in contact with
or cared for the horse. Agriculture Secretary Samuel Hayes Jr. said
concerned horse owners should contact their veterinarian. A fact sheet for
horse owners also is available through the West Nile website,
.
Also reported was confirmation [first reported 26 and 28 Sep 2000 of West
Nile virus in Bucks (2 crows), Chester (1 crow) and Delaware (1 crow)
Counties. Previously no positive birds or mosquito pools had been found in
Pennsylvania. <http://www.westnile.state.pa.us/StateSummary/>
