[6
Date: 4 Oct 2000 13:10:04 -0400
From: Mitchell, Carl J. <cjm2@cdc.gov>

Sentinel Chicken Color Unlikely to be Relevant
----------------------------------------------
In the previous West Nile Virus surveillance - USA (40) post, it was
suggested that an explanation for the poor performance of sentinel chickens
might be that _Culex_ spp. mosquitos are attracted mostly to black or dark
birds. Consequently, if White Leghorn chickens are being employed as
sentinels, they are less well-endowed to function as sentinels.
This seems a feeble explanation at best; White Leghorn chickens have been
used successfully as sentinels for Western equine encephalitis and St.
Louis encephalitis viruses in other parts of the USA. Also, _Culex_
mosquitoes typically feed mainly during crepuscular periods and at night.
The hypothesis put forward would require that such mosquitoes have night
vision sufficient for distinguishing light and dark colors.
--
Carl J. Mitchell, Sc.D.
Supervisory Research Entomologist
Centers for Disease Control
P.O. Box 2087
Fort Collins, CO 80522
<cjm2@cdc.gov>
