[7
Date: 5 Oct 2000 09:26:53 -0400
From: Walter J. Tabachnick <wjt@GNV.IFAS.UFL.EDU>

Factors Affecting the Effectiveness of Sentinel Vertebrates
------------------------------------------------------------
We read with interest the hypothesis that the failure of northeast sentinel
flocks to detect West Nile virus (WNV) was possibly due to _Culex_ not
being attracted to white chickens. We can assure readers that Florida's
experience does not support this. Both white and dark chickens attract
_Culex_, and the Florida sentinel program is a proven indicator of St.
Louis encephalitis virus transmission by _Culex nigripalpus_.
We are puzzled by the large numbers of different bird species with reported
WNV "positives", many of which are not subject to substantial mosquito
feeding, i.e., hummingbirds and a cockatiel in a 6th floor New York
apartment. In view of these, it seems far-fetched to advocate that white
chickens are the only avians not attractive in this setting.
Sentinel vertebrate surveillance can provide a near real-time measure of
local virus TRANSMISSION, but only if local vector relationships are
sufficiently understood to select a relevant sentinel vertebrate. No one
can understand the specific roles played by the various suspect WNV vector
species identified to date in the Atlantic states, and reported lack of
involvement of the sentinel chickens, based on the data reported in
ProMED-mail and on other web sites. The uncritical comparison of numbers of
sentinel chicken seroconversions with (a) numbers of dead, WNV-"positive"
wild birds, (b) wild bird serosurvey data, or (c) numbers of WNV-"positive"
mosquito pools misses the point that these surveillance tools monitor
different aspects of a complex local transmission cycle. Only documented
human cases and seroconverting sentinel vertebrates can estimate WHEN and
WHERE the infective mosquito bite occurred.
There are many possible explanations for the lack of activity in the
northeast sentinel flocks. A full assessment of the situation requires
details on the flocks, placement, diagnostics being used (are these the
same tests being used as for the wild birds?), numbers, probability of
detection. If these data substantiate that the chickens indeed have been
different, then clearly transmission has not been as dispersed as indicated
by the wild bird reports. Our hypothesis would then be that WNV
transmission in the northeast is likely multi-focal at best, and sentinels
have not been placed within areas of active transmission.
A complete disclosure of the data should be helpful in differentiating
between some of the possibilities. We continue to hope that those reporting
information will provide useful details as requested previously in several
ProMED-mail postings.
--
Walter J. Tabachnick
Jonathan F. Day
Florida Medical Entomology Laboratory
University of Florida
200 9th St, SE
Vero Beach, FL
wjt@gnv.ifas.ufl.edu>
and
Donald A. Shroyer
Medical Entomologist
Indian River Mosquito Control District
Vero Beach, Florida
